Thread Priorities & Naming

Interview Questions
1) What are thread priorities, and how are they assigned?
-->Thread priority is a number assigned to a thread that indicates the importance of the thread to the thread scheduler.
    
    Higher-priority threads usually get more CPU time compared to lower-priority threads.
    
    Java thread priorities range from:
    
    1 to 10
    Assigning Priority
    
    Priority can be assigned using:
    
    setPriority(int priority)
    Example
    class MyThread extends Thread {
    
        public void run() {
            System.out.println("Running");
        }
    }
    
    class Demo {
    
        public static void main(String[] args) {
    
            MyThread t = new MyThread();
    
            t.setPriority(8);
    
            t.start();
        }
    }



2) What is the default thread priority?
-->The default priority of every thread in Java is:
    
    5
    
    This is represented by:
        Thread.NORM_PRIORITY
        Important Point
        
        Child threads inherit the priority of their parent thread.
    

3) What are the constant values used for priorities (MIN_PRIORITY, NORM_PRIORITY, MAX_PRIORITY)?
-->Java provides predefined constants in the Thread class.
    
    Constant	Value
    Thread.MIN_PRIORITY	1
    Thread.NORM_PRIORITY	5
    Thread.MAX_PRIORITY	10
    Example
    System.out.println(Thread.MIN_PRIORITY);
    System.out.println(Thread.NORM_PRIORITY);
    System.out.println(Thread.MAX_PRIORITY);
    Output
    1
    5
    10



4) Does thread priority guarantee order of execution?
-->No, thread priority does NOT guarantee execution order.
      
      It is only a suggestion to the thread scheduler.
      
      Important Points
      Higher priority threads usually get preference
      Scheduler behavior depends on JVM and operating system
      Lower priority threads may still execute first
      Example
      
      Even if:
        t1.setPriority(10);
        t2.setPriority(1);
      
      t2 may execute before t1.



5) How to set the name of a thread & How to get the name of a thread?
-->
    
    Setting Thread Name
    
    Use:
    
    setName(String name)
    Getting Thread Name
    
    Use:
    
    getName()
    Example
    class MyThread extends Thread {
    
        public void run() {
    
            System.out.println(Thread.currentThread().getName());
        }
    }
    
    class Demo {
    
        public static void main(String[] args) {
    
            MyThread t = new MyThread();
    
            t.setName("Child Thread");
    
            t.start();
    
            System.out.println(Thread.currentThread().getName());
        }
    }
    Possible Output
    main
    Child Thread
6) What happens if two threads have the same priority?
-->If two threads have the same priority:
        
        Their execution order depends on the thread scheduler
        Usually executed using time slicing
        Important Point
        
        Execution order is unpredictable.
        
        Both threads get equal chance for CPU execution.
        When two or more threads have the same priority in Java, the Thread Scheduler (part of the JVM or the underlying OS) decides which one to
        execute first. Since Java does not guarantee a strict execution order for equal-priority threads, their behavior depends on the specific
        scheduling policy used by the platform.Common outcomes for same-priority threads include:
                Round-Robin Scheduling: The scheduler may rotate through the ready threads, giving each a fair share of CPU time.
        
                Time-Slicing: Each thread is assigned a small "time slice" or quantum. Once its time expires, the scheduler preempts it to
                                let the next thread run.
                
                First-In-First-Out (FIFO): In some implementations, the thread that entered the "Runnable" state first is executed first
                
                Arbitrary Selection: The scheduler may simply pick one thread arbitrarily to start processing.



7) Can we change thread name and priority after it starts?
-->Yes, thread name and priority can be changed even after the thread starts.

Example
class MyThread extends Thread {

    public void run() {

        System.out.println(getName());

        System.out.println(getPriority());
    }
}

class Demo {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        MyThread t = new MyThread();

        t.start();

        t.setName("New Thread");

        t.setPriority(8);
    }
}



8) What is the difference between Thread.currentThread() and this?
-->
| `Thread.currentThread()`                  | `this`                              |
| ----------------------------------------- | ----------------------------------- |
| Returns currently executing thread object | Refers to current object            |
| Static method                             | Reference variable                  |
| Can return any executing thread           | Refers only to current class object |
| Belongs to `Thread` class                 | Belongs to current instance         |
    
Example
    class MyThread extends Thread {
    
        public void run() {
    
            System.out.println(Thread.currentThread());
    
            System.out.println(this);
        }
    }
    
    If current thread is same object, both may print same result.




9) Can we call start() method twice on the same thread?
-->No, we cannot call start() twice on the same thread.
        
        If we call it again:
        
        IllegalThreadStateException
        
        is thrown.
        
        Reason
        
        A thread can be started only once.
        
        After completion:
        
        Thread enters TERMINATED state
        Dead thread cannot restart
        Example
        class MyThread extends Thread {
        
            public void run() {
        
                System.out.println("Running");
            }
        }
        
        class Demo {
        
            public static void main(String[] args) {
        
                MyThread t = new MyThread();
        
                t.start();
        
                t.start(); // Exception
            }
        }
        Output
        Running
        Exception in thread "main"
        java.lang.IllegalThreadStateException
